orthern Exposure]]''\n| Mike Monroe\n| 10 episodes\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''\n| Host\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''In Cold Blood''\n| Dick Hickock\n| \n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Cursed (2000 TV series)|Cursed]]''\n| Ricky\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Frasier]]''\n| Tom\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1994\u20132002, 2008\n| ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]''\n| [[Dr. Mark Greene]]\n| 181 episodes<br />[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama]] (1998)<br />[[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Drama Series]] (1996, 1998)<br />Nominated \u2014 [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor \u2013 Drama Series]] (1995\u201398)<br />[[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series]] (1996\u20131999)<br />[[TV Land Award]] - Icon Award (2009)<br />Nominated \u2014 [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama]] (1996\u20131997, 1999)<br />Nominated \u2014 [[Satellite Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama]] (1997)<br />Nominated \u2014 [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Drama Series]] (1997, 1999, 2001)<br />Nominated \u2014 [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series]] (1995, 2000\u201301)<br />Nominated \u2014 TV Guide Award for Actor of the Year in a Drama Series (2001)\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Zero Hour (2013 TV series)|Zero Hour]]''\n| Hank Galliston\n| 13 episodes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]]''\n| Melvin Shapiro\n| 1 episode (\"Iowa\")\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Blue Bloods (TV series)|Blue Bloods]]''\n| Owen Cairo<ref>{{cite web|url=http://2paragraphs.com/2015/11/who-is-bullit-car-owner-owen-cairo-on-blue-bloods/|title=Who Is 'Bullit' Car Owner Owen Cairo On 'Blue Bloods'?|publisher=}}</ref>\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Billions (TV series)|Billions]]''\n| Judge Whit Wilcox\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n| Patrick Griffin\n| 1 episode (\"Rape Interrupted\")\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Drunk History]]''\n| Giles Allen\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Law & Order True Crime]]''\n| Judge [[Stanley Weisberg]]\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Designated Survivor (TV series)|Designated Survivor]]''\n| [[White House Chief of Staff]] Mars Harper\n| Recurring role\n|}\n\n===Producer===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:50px;\"| Year\n! style=\"width:250px;\"| Title\n! style=\"width:150px;\"| Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''Don't Go Breaking My Heart''\n| [[Executive producer]]\n| \n|-\n| 1999\n| ''Border Line''\n| Executive producer\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[N.Y.H.C. (film)|N.Y.H.C.]]''\n| Executive producer\n| \n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[My Louisiana Sky#Film adaptation|My Louisiana Sky]]''\n| Executive producer\n| Television film<br />[[Carnegie Medal for Excellence in Children's Video]] (2002)<br />[[Daytime Emmy Award]] for Outstanding Children's Special (2002)\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Die, Mommie, Die!]]''\n| Producer\n| \n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Temple Grandin (film)|Temple Grandin]]''\n| Executive producer\n| Television film<br />[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie]] (2010)\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n* {{IMDb name|0000381}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Anthony Edwards\n|list =\n{{GoldenGlobeBestActorTVDrama 1990-2009}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAward MaleTVDrama 1994-2009}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAwards EnsembleTVDrama 1994\u20131999}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edwards, Anthony}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Santa Barbara, California]]\n[[Category:USC School of Dramatic Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Drama Actor Golden Globe (television) winners]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Drama Series Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Television producers from California]]\n[[Category:Film producers from California]]\n[[Category:American television directors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor and director|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Other people}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name           = Anthony Edwards\n| image          = AnthonyEdwards.jpg\n| caption        = Edwards at the 2002 Indy 500\n| birth_name     = Anthony Charles Edwards\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1962|7|19}}\n| birth_place    = [[Santa Barbara, California]], U.S.\n| height         = 6 ft 2 in<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000381/bio Anthony Edwards - Biography - IMDb</ref><ref>[https://notednames.com/Movies/Actor/Anthony-Edwards-Birthday-Real-Name-Age-Weight-Height/ Anthony Edwards Birthday, Real Name, Age, Weight, Height ...\n</ref>\n| weight         = 193 lbs<ref>[https://notednames.com/Movies/Actor/Anthony-Edwards-Birthday-Real-Name-Age-Weight-Height/ Anthony Edwards Birthday, Real Name, Age, Weight, Height ...</ref>\n| occupation     = Actor, director\n| years_active   = 1973\u2013present\n| spouse         = {{marriage|Jeanine Lobell|1994|2015|end=divorced}}\n| children       = 4\n| residence      = [[New York City]], U.S.\n}}\n\n'''Anthony Charles Edwards'''<ref>According to the State of California. ''California Birth Index, 1905\u20131995''. Center for Health Statistics, California Department of Health Services, Sacramento, California. At Ancestry.com</ref> (born July 19, 1962)<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2019/07/19/Famous-birthdays-for-July-19-Brian-May-Anthony-Edwards/2631563201127/|title= Famous birthdays for July 19: Brian May, Anthony Edwardsl|agency=[[United Press International]]|date=July 19, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019|archivedate=July 19, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190719123258/https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2019/07/19/Famous-birthdays-for-July-19-Brian-May-Anthony-Edwards/2631563201127/|url-status=live|quote= Actor Anthony Edwards in 1962 (age 57)}}</ref> is an American actor and director.<ref>[http://www.emmys.tv/awards/awardsearch.php Advanced Primetime Awards], Academy of Television Arts & Sciences website, retrieved 2009-04-17;</ref> He is most widely known for his role as Dr. [[Mark Greene]] on the first eight seasons of ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'', for which he received a [[Golden Globe]] award and six [[Screen Actors Guild Awards]], and was nominated for four consecutive [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series|Primetime Emmy Awards]]. Additionally, he has appeared in various movies and television shows, including ''[[Top Gun]]'', ''[[Zodiac (film)|Zodiac]]'', ''[[Miracle Mile (film)|Miracle Mile]]'', ''[[Revenge of the Nerds]]'', ''[[Planes (film)|Planes]]'', ''[[Northern Exposure]]'' and ''[[Designated Survivor (TV series)|Designated Survivor]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nEdwards was born in [[Santa Barbara, California]], the son of Erika Kem Edwards Plack ([[married and maiden names|n\u00e9e]] Weber), an artist/landscape painter, and Peter Edwards, an [[architect]].<ref name=\"filmreference\">{{cite web| url=  http://www.filmreference.com/film/80/Anthony-Edwards.html |title=Anthony Edwards Biography (1962-) |publisher= FilmReference.com |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/421652721.html?dids=421652721:421652721&FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Dec+08%2C+1950&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Peter+Edwards+and+Bride+on+Honeymoon+in+Sun+Valley&pqatl=google | title=Peter Edwards and Bride on Honeymoon in Sun Valley | date=1950-12-08}}</ref> His maternal grandfather was designer Kem Weber. He is of [[Irish people|Irish]] descent. He has two older sisters, Heidi and Ann-Marie, and two older brothers, Peter and Jeffrey. Edwards was encouraged by his parents to attend college before pursuing his interest in acting. He received a scholarship to the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Arts]] in England and studied theatre at [[University of Southern California]];{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} but by the age of nineteen was being offered enough acting work to enable him to leave college.\n\n==Career==\nEdwards' early work included a co-starring role in the TV series ''[[It Takes Two (1982 TV series)|It Takes Two]]'' with [[Richard Crenna]] and [[Patty Duke Astin]] as his parents and [[Helen Hunt]] as his sister. He made a cameo in the hit 1982 film ''[[Fast Times at Ridgemont High]]'' as \"Stoner Bud\". In 1984, he starred in the hit comedy film ''[[Revenge of the Nerds]]'' playing the main role of Gilbert Lowe, a sensitive and well-meaning nerd, Lewis' (played by [[Robert Carradine]]) best friend and later president of the Tri-Lambs. He reprised the role of Gilbert for a few brief scenes in the sequel ''[[Revenge of the Nerds II: Nerds in Paradise]]'' (1987), with his character unable to join the rest of the nerds because of a broken leg.\n\nHe starred in the Cold War-era comedy ''[[Gotcha! (film)|Gotcha!]]'' (1985) as a college student who gets wrapped up in spy antics.  It was Edwards' role as [[Lieutenant (junior grade)|LTJG]] Nick \"Goose\" Bradshaw alongside [[Tom Cruise]] in the 1986 film ''[[Top Gun]]'' that brought his first widespread public acknowledgment. His character, who died in an aviation accident, was among the most prominent and popular in the film. He appeared as a terminally ill patient in ''[[Hawks (film)|Hawks]]'' (1988) alongside [[Timothy Dalton]], another role which brought him worldwide fame.  He starred in the 1990 movie ''[[Downtown (film)|Downtown]]'' with [[Penelope Ann Miller]] and [[Forest Whitaker]]. He also played widowed veterinarian Chase Matthews, father of [[Edward Furlong]]'s character, in the [[horror film]] ''[[Pet Sematary Two]]'' (1992), a sequel to the film ''[[Pet Sematary (1989 film)|Pet Sematary]]'' in 1989. In 1992 and 1993 he played Mike Monroe in ten episodes of ''[[Northern Exposure]]''.\n\nEdwards' best-known role is as Dr. [[Mark Greene]] on the long-running TV series ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'', from the series premiere in 1994 to the end of the 8th season in 2002. The series also afforded Edwards his first opportunity to direct. Edwards' desire to pursue directing led to his request to be written out of the series. He reportedly earned $35 million for three seasons on ''ER'', which made him one of television's highest-paid actors.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dr. Benton's $27m cut|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/422517.stm|publisher=BBC News|date=17 August 1999|access-date=24 June 2012}}</ref> Edwards and his co-star [[George Clooney]] were the ones who suggested doing an episode of ''ER'' live.<ref>ER: The Complete Fourth Season, Extra Features</ref> The fourth-season premiere, \"Ambush\", was performed live twice, with an East Coast and a West Coast version.\n\nEdwards received four Primetime Emmy Award nominations for ''ER.'' He won a Golden Globe Award For Best Performance by an Actor-In a TV Series after being nominated four times and he has two Screen Actor's Guild Awards.\n\nIn 2007, Edwards appeared as SFPD inspector Bill Armstrong in [[David Fincher]]'s ''[[Zodiac (film)|Zodiac]]'', about the [[Zodiac Killer]], the notorious [[serial killer]] who terrorized [[San Francisco]] in the 1960s and 1970s.\n\nIn 2008, Edwards returned to ''ER'' to reprise his role as Dr. Greene (in flashback scenes, where he treats the dying son of character [[Catherine Banfield]]) for one episode during its 15th and final season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20080904/ap_en_ot/tv_er_anthony_edwards |title=Dr. Greene returns in `ER' final-season flashback |website=Yahoo.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080913195420/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20080904/ap_en_ot/tv_er_anthony_edwards |archivedate=2008-09-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Edwards appeared in the movie ''[[Motherhood (2009 film)|Motherhood]]'', which set a record for the biggest bomb in British cinema history by garnering \u00a388 on 11 tickets on opening weekend.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/mar/26/uma-thurman-motherhood-flop|title=The Uma Thurman film so bad it made \u00a388 on opening weekend|author=Amelia Hill|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=March 26, 2010|location=London}}</ref> ''Motherhood'' did not fare much better in the United States. earning $93,388 in three weeks of release.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=motherhood.htm |title=Motherhood (2009) |publisher= [[BoxOfficeMojo]] |access-date=March 29, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100401184751/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=motherhood.htm| archivedate= 1 April 2010| url-status= live}}</ref> At the time, he said he took the role because \"it seemed like a very organic and real thing. It really kind of reminded me of what the dynamic in a family is like.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyactor.com/interview/anthony-edwards-talks-to-daily-actor-sort-of-about-becoming-a-better-actor-as-you-get-older-working-in-nyc-and-much-more/|title=Interview: Anthony Edwards on 'Motherhood' and Becoming a Better Actor as He Gets Older|date=October 2, 2009|website=Daily Actor}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Edwards returned to episodic television with the conspiracy drama ''[[Zero Hour (2013 TV series)|Zero Hour]]'', playing the male lead Hank Galliston. After three episodes, ''Zero Hour'' was cancelled due to poor ratings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tvline.com/2013/03/01/zero-hour-cancelled-by-abc/|title=Time's Up: Zero Hour Cancelled by ABC|work=Tvline.com|date=March 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nEdwards was the voice of Echo, one of the fighter jets, in the [[Disneytoon Studios]] film ''[[Planes (film)|Planes]]'', and also voiced the character Pegleg Pirate in an episode of ''[[Blaze and the Monster Machines]]''.\n\nEdwards served as the director of the 2016 film ''[[My Dead Boyfriend]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Murthi|first=Vikram|title=\u2018My Dead Boyfriend\u2019 Exclusive Clip: Heather Graham Embarks On an Eccentric Journey To Learn About Her Deceased Companion|date=27 October 2016|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/10/my-dead-boyfriend-clip-heather-graham-katherine-moenning-anthony-edwards-1201741134/|accessdate=6 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Edwards played a recurring role as Judge [[Stanley Weisberg]] on ''[[Law & Order True Crime]]'': The Menendez Murders.\n\nIn 2018, Edwards was cast in the recurring role in the third season of [[Netflix]]'s ''[[Designated Survivor (TV series)|Designated Survivor]]'' as Mars Harper, the President\u2019s Chief of Staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/designated-survivor-anthony-edwards-julie-white-cast-in-season-3-on-netflix-1202485492/|title=\u2018Designated Survivor\u2019: Anthony Edwards & Julie White Cast In Season 3 On Netflix|last2=Petski|first2=Denise|last1=Nellie|first1=Andreeva|date=October 18, 2018|work=Deadline|access-date=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFrom 1994 to 2015, Edwards was married to Jeanine Lobell. They have one son and three daughters. He and his ex-wife resided in New York City. In 1994, Lobell, who had worked as a makeup artist, founded the [[Stila]] cosmetics line, which she then sold to [[Est\u00e9e Lauder Companies|Estee Lauder]] in 1999.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/06/business/company-news-estee-lauder-says-it-has-agreed-to-buy-stila-cosmetics.html |title=ESTEE LAUDER SAYS IT HAS AGREED TO BUY STILA COSMETICS\n |publisher=NYTimes Co. |date=1999-08-06 |accessdate=2013-02-13}}</ref>\n\nEdwards serves as chairman for Shoe4Africa, a [[non-profit organization]] that donates shoes to [[Kenyan]] athletes and aims to build the largest public children's [[hospital]] in Africa. He ran in the [[ING New York City Marathon]] on November 1, 2009 to raise funds for Shoe4Africa.<ref>{{cite web|last=Oh |first=Eunice |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20302140,00.html |title=Anthony Edwards Goes the Distance for Charity |publisher=People magazine |date=2009-09-03 |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref>\n\nSince his teenage years, Edwards has been a close friend of picture book illustrator [[Steven Kellogg]]. In 2011, Edwards's gift of $350,000 made it possible for Kellogg's complete life's work of more than 2700 illustrations to be donated to the [[Mazza Museum of International Art from Picture Books]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.findlay.edu/newsevents/news/newsreleases/2011/07/mazzakellogg_july11.htm |title=Mazza Obtains Major Collection of Kellogg Artwork |publisher=[[University of Findlay]] |date=2011-07-13 |accessdate=2011-12-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402234911/http://www.findlay.edu/newsevents/news/newsreleases/2011/07/mazzakellogg_july11.htm |archivedate=2012-04-02 }}</ref>\n\nEdwards has been a licensed private pilot (airplane single engine land) since 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aopa.org/news-and-media/all-news/2013/february/pilot/pilots-anthony-edwards |title=Pilots: Anthony Edwards |publisher= AOPA |date=2013-02-05 |accessdate=2016-08-30}}</ref>\n\nOn November 10, 2017, Edwards wrote an essay on [[Medium (website)|Medium]] in which he stated that screenwriter/producer [[Gary Goddard]] befriended and then sexually assaulted him and several of his friends \"for years\" beginning when they were 12 years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/@anthonyedwards/yes-mom-there-is-something-wrong-f2bcf56434b9|title=Yes Mom, There is Something Wrong|last=Edwards|first=Anthony|date=November 10, 2017|work=[[Medium (website)|Medium]]|accessdate=10 November 2017}}</ref><ref>Jackson McHenry, [https://www.vulture.com/2017/11/anthony-edwards-claims-producer-gary-goddard-molested-him.html \"Actor Anthony Edwards Claims Producer Gary Goddard Molested Him and His Friend As Children,\"] ''[[Vulture.com]]'', November 10, 2017.</ref> Edwards serves as Chairman of the Board of Directors of [[1in6]], a leading national organization dedicated to helping men who have had unwanted or abusive sexual experiences live healthier, happier lives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prweb.com/releases/2018/04/prweb15408838.htm|title=Actor Anthony Edwards Joins Board of 1in6, A National Nonprofit Serving Men Who Have Experienced Sexual Abuse or Assault|website=PRWeb|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref>\nEdwards is currently in a supportive and romantic relationship with longtime friend Mare Winningham\n\n==Honors and awards==\nEdwards received four Emmy nominations for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series]] for ''ER'' and won as an executive producer on [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie|Outstanding Television Movie]] winner ''[[Temple Grandin]]''.<ref name=\"NBC\"/> He earned a [[People's Choice Awards|People's Choice Award]] for Favorite Male Performer in a New Television Series (1995);<ref name=\"NBC\">[http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news.aspx?id=20080904nbc03 NBC Press Release: NBC Announces Golden Globe Winner & Emmy Nominee Anthony Edwards to Reprise His Role as Dr. Mark Greene....], originally issued 09-04-08, The Futon Critic website, retrieved 2009-04-17</ref> and won six [[Screen Actors Guild Awards]] for: Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Drama Series (1996 and 1998), and Best Ensemble Cast (1996, 1997, 1998 and 1999).<ref name=\"NBC\"/> He won the [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Award]] for Best Performance by an Actor in a Television Drama in 1998).<ref name=\"NBC\"/>\n\nEdwards also won a Daytime Emmy for the production of the underground rock documentary ''N.Y.H.C.'' (1999) and the telepic adaptation of [[Kimberly Willis Holt]]'s 1998 [[Bildungsroman|coming of age novel]] ''[[My Louisiana Sky]]'' (2001),<ref name=\"filmdotcom\"/> and earned the [[Carnegie Medal for Excellence in Children's Video|Carnegie Medal Award]] for: ''My Louisiana Sky'' (2003).<ref name=\"filmdotcom\">[http://www.film.com/celebrities/anthony-edwards/biography/14645918 Anthony Edwards Biography], Film.com website, retrieved 2009-04-17</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Films===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:50px;\"| Year\n! style=\"width:250px;\"| Title\n! style=\"width:150px;\"| Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''Big Zapper''\n| Kono's Boy\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Fast Times at Ridgemont High]]''\n| Stoner Bud\n|\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Heart Like a Wheel (film)|Heart Like a Wheel]]''\n| John Muldowney (age 15-23) \n|\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[High School U.S.A.]]''\n| Bo Middleton (Age 18)\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Revenge of the Nerds]]''\n| Gilbert Lowe\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Gotcha! (film)|Gotcha!]]''\n| Jonathan Moore \n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| \u2018\u2019[[Going for the Gold]]\u2019\u2019\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''{{sortname|The|Sure Thing}}''\n| Lance\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Top Gun]]''\n| Lt. (j.g.) Nick \"Goose\" Bradshaw\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Summer Heat (1987 film)|Summer Heat]]'' \n| Aaron \n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Revenge of the Nerds II: Nerds in Paradise]]''\n| Gilbert Lowe\n| \n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Hawks (film)|Hawks]]''\n| Deckermensky, 'Decker'\n| \n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Miracle Mile (film)|Miracle Mile]]''\n| Harry Washello\n| \n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Mr. North]]''\n| Theophilus North\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[How I Got Into College]]''\n| Kip Hammett\n| \n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Downtown (film)|Downtown]]''\n| Alex Kearney \n| \n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Pet Sematary Two]]''\n| Chase Matthews\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Delta Heat]]''\n| Mike Bishop\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''Landslide''\n| Bob Boyd\n| \n|-\n| 1993\n| ''Sexual Healing''\n| David\n| Nominated \u2014 [[CableACE Award]] for Actor in a Movie or Miniseries\n|-\n| 1994\n